When a small group of living organisms (small population) deviates from the main population from which it originates (for example, if it moves through a mountain chain or river, or moves to a new island and is difficult to return), it will often find itself in a different environment than it used to.
This new environment has different resources and competitors, so the new population will need different qualities or adaptations to be able to match them.
The original population has not changed in any way, they still need the same adjustments as before.
As the new population begins to adapt to the new environment, it eventually becomes less and less like the second population.
Over time, thousands or even millions of years, the populations will appear so different that they will not be considered the same type.
This process is called speciation, which means the formation of new species. Specialization is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
